<paragraphs>
  <title>Center of MassM</title>
  
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the location of the center of mass of the point masses tabulated below:
       
          <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
           <cell>Mass (kg)  </cell>
          <cell> x-coordinate (m)  </cell>
          <cell>y-coordinate (m) </cell>
          </row>
          <row>
          <cell> 1 </cell>
          <cell> 2</cell>
          <cell> 3</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
          <cell> 4</cell>
          <cell>-5</cell>
          <cell> 6</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>7	</cell>
            <cell>8 </cell>
            <cell>-9</cell>
           </row>
            </tabular>
            </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
         <md>
          <mrow> x_{cm} \amp  =   \frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}{m_{i}x_{i}}}{\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}{m_{i}}} = \frac{m_{1}x_{1}+m_{2}x_{2}+m_{3}x_{3}}{m_{1}+m_{2}+m_{3}} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \frac{(1\times 2) +(4\times -5) + (7\times 8)}{1+4+7} = 3.17 m</mrow>
        </md>
        <md>
          <mrow>y_{cm} \amp  =   \frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}{m_{i}y_{i}}}{\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}{m_{i}}} = \frac{m_{1}y_{1}+m_{2}y_{2}+m_{3}y_{3}}{m_{1}+m_{2}+m_{3}}  </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp  = \frac{(1\times 3) +(4\times 6) + (7\times -9)}{1+4+7} = -3.00 \,m</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the center of mass of the point masses illustrated below:
        <image source="cm1a.png" width ="50%"> </image>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        1. Find the coordinates of each mass and specify those coordinate pairs 
        beside each respective mass. 
      </p>
      <p> 
        2. Use the center of mass equations to calculate the coordinates of the center of mass. 
        </p>
        <p><m>\therefore</m> the center of mass lies at point <m>D(1.75\,m,4.87\,m).</m></p>
       </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the center of mass of the uniform sheet illustrated at right:
        <image source="cm1b.png" width ="50%"> </image>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        1. Break the body down into its two constituent parts. 
      </p>
      <p>
      2. Specify the area of each constituent part. 
      </p>
        <p>
          <m>(8m \times 10\,m = 80 \,m^{2}</m> and <m> 6\,m \times 4\,m = 24 \,m^{2})</m>
      </p>
	<p> 
    3.	Locate the coordinates of the center of mass of each constituent part. 
    The center of mass of big surface of surface area <m>80 \,m^{2}</m> 
    is at (4,5) and that for small surface of surface area <m>24 \,m^{2}</m> is at (11,2). 
    (Note: For uniform object geometrical center is taken as its center of mass.)	
      </p>
      <p>
        4. Utilize the equations shown above. 
      </p>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Note: mass is proportional to area for a uniform surface: 
          <me>
            x_{cm} =\frac{80\times 4 + 24\times 11}{80+24}=5.62\,m; 
          </me>
          <me>
            y_{cm} = \frac{80\times 5 + 24\times 2}{80+24}=4.31\,m.
          </me>
          </p>
      </answer>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the x-coordinate of a center of mass of a uniform disk of 
        radius 2R from which the mass of a small disk of radius R is 
        missing as shown in given figure.
        <image source="cm2.png" width ="30%"> </image>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We know that the center of mass of full disk of radius <m>2R</m> lies at its center (0,0).
        <me>
          \therefore\quad x_{f}= \frac{m_{s}x_{s}+m_{r}x_{r}}{m_{s}+m_{r}} =0
        </me>
        here <m>x_{f}, \quad x_{s},\quad x_{r}</m> stand for the x-coordinates of a center of 
        mass of the full disk, small disk, and real disk, and <m>m_{s}, \quad m_{r}</m> 
        stand for the mass of a small disk which is missing, and the mass of the real disk. 
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad x_{r}= -\frac{m_{s}x_{s}}{m_{r}} =-\frac{(\rho \pi R^{2})(-R)}{\rho[\pi(2R)^{2}-\pi R^{2}]}=\frac{R}{3}
        </me>
        <term>Note:</term> mass is proportional to area for a uniform surface. <m>\rho</m> is a density of the disk.
         </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the x-coordinate of the center of mass of a rod of length L 
        whose mass per unit length varies as <m>\lambda = \alpha x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Consider a rod of length <m>L</m> of mass <m>M</m> and has mass 
        per unit length as <m>\lambda =\frac{\,dm}{\,dl}= \alpha x </m>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad \,dm = \lambda \,dl = \lambda \,dx \quad (say)
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad x_{cm}= \frac{1}{M}\int x\,dm =\frac{1}{M}\int\limits_{0}^{L} x\lambda\,dx =\frac{1}{M}\int\limits_{0}^{L} x(\alpha x)\,dx 
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{\alpha}{M}\int\limits_{0}^{L} x^{2}\,dx  = \frac{\alpha}{M}\left(\frac{x^{3}}{3}\right)_{0}^{L}=\frac{\alpha L^{3}}{3M}
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Three bricks, each 2 inch thick by 3 inch wide by 6 inch long, 
        are placed one on top of the other overhanging the edge of a table. 
        What is the maximum distance <m>x</m> that the top brick can extend 
        beyond the edge of the table without falling off the table?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Block(s) can be balanced at the edge of anything if its center of mass lies 
        before edge or at least at the edge of that thing. 
        <image source="cm9.png" width ="45%"> </image>
      </p>
      <p>
        Maximum overhung = center of mass of blocks system. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Maximum overhung for blue (I) brick = its center of mass from the free end =<m>\frac{l}{2} </m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Center of mass for red (II) and blue (I) bricks
         <me>
          = \left\{\frac{m\frac{l}{2}+m\left(\frac{l}{2}+\frac{l}{2}\right)}{2m}\right\} =\frac{3l}{4}.
        </me>
        Center of mass for green (III), red (II) and blue (I) bricks
        <me>
         = \left\{\frac{2m\frac{3l}{4}+m\left(\frac{3l}{4}+\frac{l}{2}\right)}{3m}\right\} =\frac{11l}{12}.
        </me>
        Which is the maximum overhung for three bricks system. Using torque equation <xref ref="sec_fourth-torque"/>, 
        we can get same condition, if we set <m>x_{n}(nM) = x_{1}M</m>. 
        Where <m>x_{1}</m> is C.M. of first object, and <m>n</m> stands for number 
        of objects. Maximum overhung, 
        <me>
          x= x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots.
        </me>
         </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A solid sphere is cut into half and stacked on top of each other as shown in figure:
        <image source="cmhemisp.png" width ="35%"> </image>
        Find its center of mass.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The center of mass of a hemisphere of radius <m>a</m> is given by 
        <me>
          z_{1} = \frac{\int\limits_{0}^{M} z\,dm}{\int\limits_{0}^{M} \,dm} =\frac{1}{M}\int\limits_{0}^{a} z(\rho \pi r^{2}\,dz)
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{1}{\frac{2}{3}\pi a^{3}\rho}\int\limits_{0}^{a} z(\rho \pi r^{2})\,dz = \frac{3}{2a^{3}}\int\limits_{0}^{a}  r^{2} z\,dz 
        </me>
        here <m>r</m> is the radius of a slice at height <m>z</m> and thickness <m>\,dz</m>. 
        Since <m>z^{2}=a^{2}-r^{2} </m> we have- 
        <me>
          2z\,dz = -2r\,dr \quad \therefore \quad z\,dz=-r\,dr
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore \quad z_{1} =-\frac{3}{2a^{3}}\int\limits_{a}^{0}  r^{3} \,dr = -\frac{3}{2a^{3}}\left[\frac{a^{4}}{4}\right]_{a}^{0} 
        </me>
        <me>
          = \frac{3}{2a^{3}}\left[\frac{a^{4}}{4}\right] = \frac{3}{8}a
        </me>
       Hence, the center of mass of the two stacked hemispheres is given by
       <me>
        z_{cm} = \frac{m_{1}z_{1}+{m_{2}z_{2}}}{m_{1}+m_{2}}
       </me>
       <me>
        =\frac{\frac{M}{2}(\frac{3}{8}a)+{\frac{M}{2}(a+\frac{3}{8}a})}{M}=\frac{7}{8}a
       </me>
       </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>
  

<paragraphs>
  <title>Rotational Equilibrium</title>
 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Write the torque equation about the specified axis for the forces indicated in the figure:
      <image source="rd1.png" width ="35%"> </image>
       </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <me>
        \sum \Gamma = -(10N)(2m) +10N(x) -F_{1}(1m)-F_{2}y_{1}=0 
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Write the torque equation about the specified axis for the forces indicated below:
      <image source="rd2.png" width ="35%"> </image>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <me>
      \sum \Gamma = +f(4m) -N(3m) +w(0)-(T\sin\theta)(3m)+(T\cos\theta )(4m)=0 
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A symmetrical beam of weight <m>w_{1} = 400 \,N</m> and length <m>2 \,m</m> is 
      suspended from the ceiling on one end by a hinge and on the other by a wire 
      also of length <m>2 \,m</m> so that both beam and wire make an angle of <m>30^{o}</m> 
      with the ceiling as shown in the figure below. Suspended from the junction of wire 
      and beam is a weight <m>w_{2}= 300\, N</m>. What is the tension in the cable 
      and the horizontal and vertical components of the force on the beam at the hinge?
      <image source="rd5.png" width ="35%"> </image>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
      <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          List given quantities <m>w_{1} = 400 \,N, \quad w_{2} = 400\, N, \quad\theta = 30^{o}, \quad L = 2 \,m</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Draw the forces acting on the beam and resolve them into components.
          <image source="rd5a.png" width ="55%"> </image>
        </li>
        <li>
          Choose an axis and specify the perpendicular distances from each line of action to that axis.
        </li>
        <li>
          Write equations: 
          <me>
            \sum F_{x} = T \cos\theta - F_{x} = 0 
          </me>
          and 
          <me>
            \sum F_{y} = F_{y}+T \sin\theta - w_{1}-w_{2} = 0
          </me>
          <md>
            <mrow> \sum \Gamma \amp  = -w_{1}\frac{(L\cos\theta)}{2}- w_{2}(L\cos\theta)+(T\cos\theta)(L\sin\theta) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp  + (T\sin\theta)(L\cos\theta) = 0 </mrow>
          </md>
           </li>
           <li>
            Solve to get answers: 
            <me>
              T=\frac{(\frac{w_{1}}{2}+w_{2})L\cos\theta}{2L\sin\theta\cos\theta} =500\,N;
            </me>
            <me>
              F_{x}=T\cos\theta =433\,N;
            </me>
            <me>
              F_{y}=w_{1}+w_{2}-T\sin\theta =450\,N 
            </me>
          </li>
      </ol>
       </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A uniform rod of length 1 meter and of weight 10 Newtons is resting against 
      a vertical wall with its base 0.5 meters from the bottom of the wall. 
      If a 20 Newton weight is suspended from the rod from a point 3/4 of the 
      way up the rod, what is the minimum coefficient of friction that will keep 
      the rod from slipping on the floor? Assume there is no friction between 
      the rod and the vertical wall.
      <image source="rd6a.png" width ="25%"> </image>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Given: <m>L=1\,m,\quad w_{1}=10\,N, \quad w_{2}=20\,N, \quad x=0.5\,m,</m>
           <image source="rd6b.png" width ="25%"> </image>
           <me>
            \frac{S}{L} =\frac{3}{4}; 
          </me>
          <me>
            \cos\theta =\frac{x}{L} = \frac{0.5\,m}{1\,m} =0.5 
          </me>
          <me>\therefore\quad \theta=60^{o}</me>
        <me>
          \sum F_{x} = f-N_{2}=0
        </me>
       
        <me>
         \text{and}\quad \sum F_{y} = N_{1}-w_{1}-w_{2}=0
        </me>
        <me>
          \sum \Gamma  = f\cdot 0+N_{2}L\sin\theta - N_{1}\cdot 0-w_{1}\cdot \frac{x}{2} -w_{2}\left(\frac{S}{L}\right)\cos\theta=0
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{but}\quad f=\mu N_{1}
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{hence,}\quad N_{2}.1.\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} =10(0.25)+20(\frac{3}{4})(0.5)
        </me>
        <me>
          or,\quad N_{2}=11.547 \,N
        </me>
       <me>
        \text{and}\quad f=N_{2}=11.547 N; N_{1}=w_{1}+w_{2}=10+20=30\,N
       </me>
       <me>
        \therefore\quad \mu=\frac{f}{N_{1}}=\frac{11.547\,N}{30\,N} = 0.385
       </me>
      </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A uniform rod of length L = 1 meter and mass <m>m_{1} = 10 \,kg</m> is suspended as 
      shown in the figure below, making an angle of <m>\theta = 30^{o}</m> with the 
      horizontal and supporting a second unknown mass <m>m_{2}</m>. The support wire 
      on the left is horizontal, the support wire on the top makes an angle of 
      <m>\theta = 30^{o}</m> with the rod, and the other wire on the right 
      is vertical. The top wire is attached at a point S = 0.75 m up the rod from 
      the left. 
      <image source="rd4.png" width ="25%"> </image>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          What is the tension <m>T_{1}</m> in the wire on the left? 
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the tension <m>T_{2}</m>  in the wire on top?
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the tension <m>T_{3}</m>  in the wire on the right?
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the mass <m>m_{2}</m>?
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <sidebyside widths="45% 12%">
        <image source="rd4b.png"> </image>
        <image source="rd4c.png"> </image>
      </sidebyside>
      Given: <m>L=1\,m,\quad m_{1}=10 \,kg,\quad \theta=30^{o},\quad S =0.75\,m </m> 
      <men xml:id="eqn-trq1">
        \sum F_{x} = T_{2}\sin\phi-T_{1}=0;
      </men>
      <me>
        \text{and}\quad \sum F_{y} = T_{2}\cos\phi-w_{1}-T_{3}=0
      </me>
      <men xml:id="eqn-trq2">
        \therefore \quad T_{3}=T_{2}\cos\phi-w_{1}
      </men>
      <men xml:id="eqn-trq3">
        \sum \Gamma = T_{2}S\sin\theta - w_{1}\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)\cos\theta-T_{3}L\cos\theta=0
      </men>
      <men xml:id="eqn-trq4">
       \text{also}\quad  \sum F_{y} = T_{3}-w_{2}=0;
      </men>
      <me>
        \text{and}\quad  w_{1} = m_{1}g =98N, \qquad w_{2} = m_{2}g.
      </me>
      from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-trq3"/>
      <me>
        T_{2}S\sin\theta -T_{3}L\cos\theta = w_{1}\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)\cos\theta
      </me>
      <me>
        T_{2}S\sin\theta -\left(T_{2}\cos\phi-w_{1}\right)L\cos\theta = w_{1}\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)\cos\theta
      </me>
      <me>
        T_{2}S\sin\theta-T_{2}\cos\theta L\cos\theta=w_{1}\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)\cos\theta-w_{1}L\cos\theta  
         </me>
      <me>
        T_{2}=\left\{\frac{-0.5\times w_{1}\times L\cos\theta}{S\sin\theta-L\cos^{2}\theta}\right\}=113.16N
      </me>
      <me> [\because cos\phi=sin2\theta=cos\theta] \quad at \theta=30^o</me>
      Hence, from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-trq2"/>
      <me>
        T_{3}=0,
      </me>
      from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-trq1"/>, we have -
      <me>
        T_{1}=T_{2}\sin\phi= T_{2}\sin\theta=56.58\,N,
      </me>
      <me>
        w_{2}=T_{3}=0,
      </me>
      <me>
        m_{2}=\frac{w_{2}}{g}=0
      </me>
      </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A block with a square base measuring <m>a \times a</m> and height <m>h</m> 
      is placed on an inclined plane of angle <m>\theta</m>. The coefficient of friction 
      is <m>\mu </m> and the angle of the incline is gradually increased. Find the condition 
      at which block tip over before it begins to slide.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The block will not slide if the coefficient of friction <m>\mu_{s} \lt \tan\theta</m>. 
      In other words, sliding begins only when <m>\theta</m> becomes the angle of repose <m>\phi</m>. 
      The block will toppled down once the line of action of weight pass throgh the edge of the block, 
      i.e. when normal force acts along the edge (point of rotation) of block as shown in figure below. 
      <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
        <image source ="toppling1.png"> </image>
        <image source="toppling2.png"> </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </p>
    <p>
      From first figure, we have - 
      <me>
        f_{s}=mg\sin\theta 
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{and}\quad N=mg\cos\theta
      </me>
      Divide these equations and substitute <m>f_{s}=\mu_{s}N</m>, we get- 
      <men xml:id="eqn-topple1">
        \tan\theta = \mu_{s} 
      </men>
        If <m>\theta </m> is gradually increasing to <m>\theta=\phi </m> [second figure], then at the instant 
        of toppling, normal force acts along the bottom edge of block which is the point of 
        rotation. Hence the total torque must be zero (i.e., <m> \Gamma=0</m> at rotational equilibrium). 
        <me>
          \therefore \quad mg\sin\theta \left(\frac{h}{2}\right) -mg\cos\theta \left(\frac{a}{2}\right) =0
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad mg\sin\theta \left(\frac{h}{2}\right) =mg\cos\theta \left(\frac{a}{2}\right)
        </me>
         <men xml:id="eqn-topple2">
        \tan\theta = \frac{a}{h} 
      </men>
      Now, from eqns. <xref ref="eqn-topple1"/> and <xref ref="eqn-topple2"/>, 
        if <m>\mu_{s}  \gt \frac{a}{h}</m>, it will tip over before slide, and  
        if <m>\mu_{s}  \lt \frac{a}{h}</m>, it will slide before toppling.
    </p>
  </solution>
 </example>

 <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A uniform 10m beam of mass 300kg extends over a ledge. The beam is not attached, 
      but simply rests on the surface. A 60kg man intends to position the beam in such 
      a way that he can walk to the end of it. What is the maximum distance the beam 
      can extend past end of the ledge and still allow him to perform this feat?
      <image source ="re7.png" width="40%"> </image>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The beam can be balanced if it is placed on the edge of ledge by its new center 
      of mass, <m>P</m> (i.e., the center of mass of beam and man system). Here <m>o</m> is 
      the center of mass of a beam only.  <image source ="re7a.png" width="40%"> </image>
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>x</m> be the distance of beam overhung past the edge of ledge, 
      then from free -body diagram, we have -
      <me>
        \sum F_{y} = N-Mg-mg =0
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore \quad N = (M+m)g 
      </me>
      Since the beam is at static equilibrium. Now,
      <me>
        \sum \Gamma = Mg\left(\frac{l}{2}-x\right) -mgx =0
      </me>
       This is a total torque about the new center of mass, <m>P</m> (or the point of rotation). 
       <me>
        \text{or,}\quad \frac{Ml}{2}-Mx =mx
       </me>
       <me>
        \therefore \quad x= \frac{Ml}{2(M+m)} = \frac{300\times 10}{2\times(300+60)} =4.17\,m 
       </me>
      <term> Alternative:</term> we can solve this problem using center of mass formula, 
      <me>
        x_{cm} = \frac{m_{1}x_{1}+m_{2}x_{2}}{m_{1}+m_{2}} = \frac{300\times 5 + 60\times 10}{300+60} = 5.83\,m
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore \quad x= l-x_{cm} =10-5.83 = 4.17\,m
      </me>
      </p>
  </solution>
 </example>
</paragraphs>
</section>
